post_text:
“On this day... 19 years ago 246 people went to sleep in preparation for their morning flights. 2,606 people went to sleep in preparation for work in the morning. 343 firefighters went to sleep in preparation for their morning shift. 60 police officers went to sleep in preparation for morning patrol. 8 paramedics went to sleep in preparation for the morning shift. None of them saw past 10:00am Sept 11, 2001. In one single moment life may never be the same. As you live and enjoy the breaths you take today and tonight before you go to sleep in preparation for your life tomorrow, kiss the ones you love, snuggle a little tighter, and never take one second of your life for granted.”

💛

#wewillneverforget

post_text:
Thanks to everyone doing their part to keep everyone safe! Keep up the symptom checks! If you have any questions about sending your child to school, it is best to keep them home until you can speak to Nurse Julie. We truly understand how frustrating the one symptom and sibling rules are, but the IDPH is doing this out of safety and to hopefully slow the spread. If you've had any known exposure to COVID, please keep your child home. We are working hard to keep students in cohorts to minimize exposure to other kids. We will struggle to stay in person, if these precautions aren't followed outside of school (masks, 6 feet of distance, etc).

Here is our area testing information:

OSF Prompt Care Covid Hotline 833.673.5669. They will make you an appointment and offer drive-thru testing seven days a week, three times a day at 10:00, 2:00, and 6:00. They will bill your insurance or charge $99 if you do not have any insurance.

post_text: Not that this week isn't crazy enough, we are probably also the first school in Illinois who has one of our fire drills completed! Our alarm was accidently bumped and set off, requiring us to follow our emergency procedures and exit the building. You may have also heard the sirens going off in town. We are ALL safe and sound and incredibly PROUD of the swift, calm action of our staff and students! Typically we have several announced drills before a "surprise" one so that we can make students well aware and prepared. We just wanted to make our families aware of the added craziness of our second day. #safetyfirst

post_text: We are very excited to officially begin the year tomorrow and see our students back in action! After months of planning and preparation, we are here! (Preschool friends, we can't wait to see you after Labor Day!) We truly want to share our sincere thanks to ALL of our students, families, and amazing staff members that have ALL worked diligently together to prepare for this big day! We know this day looks so much different than years past, but our MES family has grown even stronger and we will conquer anything thrown our way. The big keys to this school year is showing kindness, grace to all, and FLEXIBILITY! As a parent in this climate, it is key to have several back up childcare plans as we work through any COVID19-related health issues.

shared_text:
Marseilles Police Department
August 15 at 11:04 AM ·

The Marseilles Police Dept. is currently investigating a report of an attempt to lure a minor into a vehicle, last night, in the area of Capris Ln. and Broadway St. The person allegedly offered the minor a ride but did not get out of the vehicle. When the minor refused and left, the vehicle drove away. A Facebook post is being circulated stating a vehicle/person with the same description was also reported in Mendota and/or Princeton. Both departments stated that there have been NO reports involving this vehicle or person. We caution the sharing of this type of information without verifying it with local authorities. Please call the Marseilles Police Department at 815-795-2131 with any questions. We will provide updates as available. Thanks and Be Safe!

post_text: Thanks so much to our Rotarians! We always need headphones!
shared_text:
Marseilles Rotary Club 5313
July 31 at 7:42 AM ·

MARSEILLES ROTARY MAY BE OUT, BUT NOT DOWN: On behalf of the Club, new Rotary Foundation Chairperson Silas Parker applied and received a matching grant to purchase 180 pairs of headphones for Marseilles Elementary School. This obviously comes just in time when electronic learning has become more critical than ever in education. This was a matching grant from
District 6420 and Club members gave $591 and then this was matched by the District's contribution of $593.40 for a total of $1,184.40. Thanks to Silas for his grant preparation, to the Club members who contributed to this project and to Rotary District 6420.

District 6420 and Club members gave $591 and then this was matched by the District's contribution of $593.40 for a total of $1,184.40. Thanks to Silas for his grant preparation, to the Club members who contributed to this project and to Rotary District 6420.

post_text: Let’s work together to keep kids safe!
shared_text:
Marseilles Police Department
July 29 at 12:33 PM ·

CURFEW REMINDER: The Marseilles Police Department enforces the Marseilles Juvenile Curfew Ordinance. This helps reduce overnight crime and provide for the care, safety and protection of juveniles and other Marseilles residents.

Marseilles Code of Ordinance: 132.02 (Curfew)
(A)(1) It is unlawful for a person of 16 or more years of age but less than 18 years of age to be present at or upon any public building, place, street or highway, between 10:00 p.m. and 6:00 a.m. unless accompanied and supervised by a parent, legal guardian.
(A)(2) It is unlawful for a person less then 16 years of age to be present at or upon any public building, place, street or highway, between 9:00 p.m. and 6:00 a.m. unless accompanied and supervised by a parent, legal guardian, or other adult.

If you are found to be in violation of this ordinance, you could be cited and fined. Parents can be charged as well.

Thanks and be safe!

Please register your students regardless of your choice of learning placement ( remote or in school ). We understand that as our guidelines change, your decisions may change also. We are working on plans to best serve our students with accurate information, and our transition team needs accurate numbers for planning.

All families are responsible for paying the new $10 technology fee. It will not be waived with verification of Direct Certification Benefits. As always, our secretaries are here to help and answer any questions you may have (usually with a smile on their face 😊).

We will not be holding our traditional, large in-person registration so please register online ASAP, DO NOT WAIT. New families and returning are also welcome to call and set up an appointment to register with Katie in person by calling 815-795-2428.

Our transition back to school team met this morning and worked hard on our plans for 20-21! We appreciate the problem solving and thoughtfulness of our staff members.

We know you are anxious to hear our plans and we are working hard to finalize everything (and note everything can change with updated IDPH / CDC guidance).

The one thing we are excited to announce is that all of our classroom spaces will be air conditioned for the start of school! We had been adding air area by area slowly, but with the help of the CARES grant we are completing it this summer.

Stay tuned for updates!

post_text: Great resources!
shared_text:
Run Today for Tomorrow is in LaSalle County, Illinois.
May 28 at 5:05 PM · Illinois ·

I wanted to share these resources that I put together for LaSalle County. You're more likely to encounter someone having a mental health crisis than you are someone having a heart attack, so it is so important to have these resources handy in the time of a crisis. If you don't save them for yourself, please at least save them as a resource to give to a friend or loved one who may need them one day. No problem is too big or too small to talk about. Even the strongest of people could use a little help once in a while. Please find the strength to take that first step to bettering yourself, the world needs you here. #YourStoryIsntOver
We will be handing out these resource flyers at the book display on June 27th if you or someone would like some. If any businesses would like a copy to display, please don't hesitate to reach out and we'll happily bring one by💛

May 26 at 12:52 PM ·

Prairie Fox Books is excited to announce our first kids’ writing and art contest!

From June 1st to August 1st, kids can send in stories, artwork, or comics, and we will choose 10 to comprise our first kids’ zine. Plus, one art piece will be chosen to be the cover!

This is open to kids in 1st through 8th grades. If you’re not chosen to be in this zine, don’t give up—we’ll do this again!

For our first zine, feel free to use anything for inspiration. We can’t wait to see what you create!

post_text: “Last day” post from Mrs. Raikes
shared_text:
Lee Ann Raikes
May 19 at 10:52 AM ·

Not the end of the school year any of us envisioned; however, what a year to remember! I miss all of my MES family! I am grateful for the time we did have together learning and growing. I know that the bond will remain forever. I wish all my colleagues, students, families, and the Marseilles community a happy and healthy summer. Until we see each other again, here is this year’s last MES Dance Party celebration. I can’t wait until we dance together again! Keep grooving! Peace and love to all you peeps!💕☮️✌️😘 #togetherwearebetter #Panthers150

Marseilles Police Department
May 18 at 1:39 PM ·

The Marseilles Police department is actively monitoring the Illinois River Levels, The current level has just raised to 23.28 and is predicted crest at 24.01 late this evening early morning. The current voluntary evacuation is at 23 feet and the mandatory evacuation is 24.5 per the Marseilles Flood Safety Plan. The Marseilles Police Department will continue to monitor the river predictions and will relay any further instructions as more information comes available. You can monitor the river activity on the National Weather Service NOAA Hydrologic prediction at Illinois River at Morris.

Crossbridge Community Church has provided several districts (including MES) with food bags for many years. They would like to continue to help families in need and could use some donations. See the information below:

post_text:
Good Afternoon MES!

As I’m sure you are aware, I am truly saddened to share that Governor’s press conference today has focused on schools. We officially are “closed” for in-person learning for the rest of this academic year. We will continue to provide remote learning through the use of paper packets and online options. We will also provide meals with the next batch coming the week of April 27 along with new paper packets that week if you are in need.

We will continue to update you as we receive more guidance from the Illinois State Board of Education but please know that students will not be retained to the same grade by us or “punished” in any way. We truly want to focus on how we can help our families as we process this news together. Please continue to check your emails, our Facebook, and website to stay up-to-date as we work through the many questions and details to “end” the school year.

You can always leave us a message at 815-795-2162 and a staff member will be in contact within 24 hours.

Take Care!
Brenda Donahue - Superintendent

April 4 at 9:44 PM ·

*NEW COVID-19 Housing Payment Assistance Program

This new program will provide financial assistance for two months of rent or mortgage (including escrow) for those that have been affected by the COVID-10 pandemic.

Must be within the CSBG 125% Income Guidelines.
Must have documentation showing you have been off work/loss of hours by your employer due to a closure of a business or proof from a doctor that you are being quarantined due to the virus.

Since all TCOC offices are closed to the public, in order to follow the social distancing order, please contact an Outreach Worker by email at:
(Melinda, Nancy or Kay): mtemple@tcochelps.org, nhillenbrand@tcochelps.org, ktownsend@tcochelps.org

Any questions, please call the main office at 1-800-323-5434, or email Neddie at neddie@tcochelps.org.

March 21 at 10:18 PM ·

Parents, I'm setting up several "classrooms" for digital mathematical escape rooms and room activities for other content areas, as well..

If you'd like access, go to student.breakoutedu.com. You'll have to set up an account once you're in the site.

Once there, if you'd like access to the LOWER ELEMENTARY activities, use code: MKCN6S

If you'd like access to the ELEMENTARY activities, use code: XDJI52 (That's a capital i.)

If you'd like access to the MIDDLE SCHOOL activities, use code: Z3WJJ2

If you'd like access to strictlry ALGEBRA, use code: 5BS3G3

If you'd like access to the HIGH SCHOOL activities, use code: LSVM7Z

If you'd like access to the activities for OLDER FOLKS ( ;) ), use code: RLZX3U

I will be posting a few each week for each level. These will be mostly mathematics activities, but there are some other content areas included. :)

post_text:
Per Governor Pritzker's hold in place order, MES will be closed through at least April 7th with a return date of April 8th (as of right now). We are sure many of you will have questions, but please give us time to work through the details, get guidance from the IL State Board of Education, and make any adjustments or plans. We will continue to communicate with you as we all work together in unprecedented times and regardless, we will continue with our eLearning efforts for our kids starting again on Monday, March 30th. Thankfully our Spring Break was already scheduled for next Monday 3/23 - Friday 3/27, so our teachers and staff are NOT expected to be to be working. We have placed orders for more meals and will be in touch after break regarding distribution.

Stay safe and well!

post_text:
We fielded a complaint and are disheartened given the current unprecedented and uncharted circumstances.

Please note that districts are required to provide absolutely ZERO instruction to families the next four days. We know this does not replace our educators but is better than “no instruction at all”. We have made the pledge to do our best and we are extremely proud of our staff for taking this approach and for their efforts today.

Our first ever E-learning day was a success on our end! Our staff ALL pulled together in less than a week, students met via Google Classroom and Zoom, students interacted at museums throughout the state virtually, and our staff packed hundreds of food bags! Wow!

Please post a picture in the comments of some learning from today and we will do a drawing!

Governor JB Pritzker is mandating school closure from 3/17-3/30. Since we are fully prepared, it makes zero sense to be here on Monday to limit exposure. To be clear there is NO SCHOOL Monday 3/16 through Monday 3/30. The first potential day back is Tuesday 3/31. He is also calling for strict social distancing procedures.

We will begin utilizing our E-Learning days on Monday. Please check your emails over the last days regarding this. We will also re-send this information for you.

If you need to pick up your student's medication that we have in our nurse's office, please plan to be here Monday from 9-10 or call the main office to set up an alternative time (815) 795-2428.

We will be in further contact regarding meal pick-up after our delivery on Monday.

Thanks for your understanding during this unprecedented situation.

Hello MES Families - We wanted to update you that we are continuing to monitor and work on plans in the event of a school closure due to COVID-19 with various agencies. You will be notified of closures if they occur through our typical system as well as Facebook and our website. We are submitting State E-Learning plans for approval as a precautionary factor to prevent a loss of learning for our students and as directed by the IL State Board of Education. We are continuing to be diligent with cleaning and frequent hand washing and we ask that you do the same at home and follow CDC recommendations.

As we are preparing learning plans, we are reaching out to see if you have internet access. IF you require paper copies, please respond to your student's teacher and we will do our best to distribute ahead of time. Otherwise, you will be emailed a link through our Teacherease system to access class materials.

https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/index.html

What is easy to get into, but hard to get out of?

post_text:
Now that second semester and Winter are here just a reminder to make sure that all of your contact information is up-to-date in Teacherease in the event we need to cancel school. You can log in and make changes yourself or call the office at 815-795-2428 for assistance.

Also, just a reminder to call your student in if they are going to be absent for the day. We appreciate a call before 9:00. If you do not call in, the absence is considered unexcused and has a harder impact for truancy. Our attendance line is 815-795-8795 where you can leave a message.

Packets with PSAT test scores and course placements are being sent home this week with your 8th grade student. Student's with IEP's and 504's will not be receiving a packet.

Each student should have a Course Selection Sheet and a letter with an explanation. OTHS' Open House will be on Wednesday, January 15th.

Please contact Lauren Yates or Kim Swords if you have any questions 815-433-1323.

Responding will be the Marseilles Police department, Marseilles Ambulance and the Marseilles Fire department, Also involved in this event will be Ottawa Central Dispatch. Again this is ONLY A DRILL. Thanks and Be safe.

post_text: TNT sends out a HUGE thank you for all the acts of kindness during #WorldKindnessWeek2019. Our members who busy working to sort and package the books that will be sent to Africa-(global). Also, we have many food items that will allow us to fill the local micro-pantry (community) when need be. We hope that this week started a cycle of kind acts and leads us all to be good humans. We all know that the world is better when we are better! We are grateful for the overwhelming support! We ❤ our community! #Worldkindnessday #Panthers150 #giveback #bekind

post_text: TNT is honored to be a part of the holiday events in our beautiful community of Marseilles. Part of our message is incorporating daily exercise to obtain that natural high as opposed to finding it elsewhere in inappropriate ways. Why not get your day started with some fresh air, friends, family, and a holiday run/walk? 💪😉This time of the year can be stressful and exercise is the best medicine to help reduce that! All proceeds go to TNT, who in turn give back to the community. Please come out and enjoy the fun! #Panthers150 #giveback #volunteer

TNT is holding their annual quilt raffle. This beautiful quilt is once again made by the sister of former MES employee, Donna Cynar, in her honor. The proceeds made from this quilt raffle go back into cancer research in our community/county. The drawing will be held during the junior high concert on Tuesday, December 10. Tickets will also be sold at the door. As always, thank you so much for the support of TNT!
